<div id="review_18838770" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/18838770" />
    <a title="Ruth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/335159-ruth"><img alt="Ruth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1491245404p2/335159.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/18838770?book_show_action=true">Mar 28, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ruth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ruth" href="/user/show/335159-ruth">Ruth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer18838770" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6184107313021334051">World War II was the leitmotif of my childhood, bracketed by my memories of Pearl Harbor Day ( “Go outside and play, children. We’re listening to the radio.”) and VJ Day, when a parade of cars jammed Pacific Coast Highway in Laguna. The photo of a dead American Marine half-buried in the sands of a Pacific Island is an image I’ve carried with me all my life.<br/><br/>So I was predisposed to read this book. It’s a big, fat, old-fashioned novel with a myriad of characters and plots, held together by the War,</span>
  <span id="freeText6184107313021334051" style="display:none">World War II was the leitmotif of my childhood, bracketed by my memories of Pearl Harbor Day ( “Go outside and play, children. We’re listening to the radio.”) and VJ Day, when a parade of cars jammed Pacific Coast Highway in Laguna. The photo of a dead American Marine half-buried in the sands of a Pacific Island is an image I’ve carried with me all my life.<br /><br />So I was predisposed to read this book. It’s a big, fat, old-fashioned novel with a myriad of characters and plots, held together by the War, and a few actual intercrossings. It must have been a major undertaking to write, both in terms of the number of characters and in the amount of background research involved. The writing, however, is pedestrian, except for a few outstanding incidences where Piercy’s background as a poet shines through.<br /><br />All told, though, this book in its sheer size (770 pages) is “too much of a muchness” as my grandmother used to say. Certainly for the last ¼ of its pages I felt as if I were on a forced march.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6184107313021334051" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


