    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_53039553" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/53039553" />
    <a title="Melody" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/442005-melody"><img alt="Melody" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/53039553?book_show_action=true">Apr 17, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melody" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melody" href="/user/show/442005-melody">Melody</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer53039553" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2157474730879985454">Wow. This book was spectacular. I genuinely cared about the characters (whether I liked them or in some cases quite didn&apos;t) and they were written so honestly and accurately, at times I would think &quot;I should look this person up to find out more about their life&quot; as if they were real people! It sounds from the epilogue like Piercy put a massive amount of research into this book, and I think that is part of why the stories are so compelling. Also, Piercy writes about women&apos;s lives with such incredi</span>
  <span id="freeText2157474730879985454" style="display:none">Wow. This book was spectacular. I genuinely cared about the characters (whether I liked them or in some cases quite didn't) and they were written so honestly and accurately, at times I would think "I should look this person up to find out more about their life" as if they were real people! It sounds from the epilogue like Piercy put a massive amount of research into this book, and I think that is part of why the stories are so compelling. Also, Piercy writes about women's lives with such incredible accuracy... describing the wide variety of ways we might feel about working, relationships, sex, whatever. It's all spot on and gives validity to the diversity of feelings and preferences out there as well as recognizes the strength of women and the breadth of ways that strength might be used. It's one of the rare books that, despite being extremely long (nearly 800 pgs), I wasn't in a hurry for it to end. And, for the record, I am not a person particularly interested in WWII - an interest or awareness of WWII events is not at all necessary to enjoy this book. The history is interesting, the characters are what grabs you (or me at least). </span>
  <a data-text-id="2157474730879985454" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


